name: Blue Bay Mahia, Beachfront Bliss
description:
Relax and enjoy uninterrupted seaviews from our comfortable beachfront Bach. The living, dining and two main bedrooms all have views across bay. With decks on both northern and southern sides you can enjoy outdoor dining most days.
Opoutama beach is a lovely sandy beach; great for young children & only a short walk away through the reserve.
The Opoutama store is a handy 10min walk away.
Minimum 3 night stay over long weekends.
Linen can be arranged for an extra charge.

description:
Located 5mins out of the Tolaga Bay we have a sunny modern studio room with independent access adjacent to our main farm house. It has a queen sized bed, desk & chairs, modern ensuite bathroom, area for making tea/coffee/toast and a fridge.

We are a working farm so plenty going on.

Beaches within a minutes drive include - Kaiaua, Tolaga Bay Wharf & Cooks Cove walkway. Plenty of food options nearby or you can head up to Tokomaru Bay to the Te Puka Tavern or get a famous Paua Pie at Cafe35.

My husband Bruce and I have a busy farm at Tolaga Bay, on the beautiful East Coast, just 45 minutes north of Gisborne.

Have operated a homestay for many years, and love meeting new people.
We are well travelled and love our sport and the outdoors. 
Lake Waikaremoana is our fav family place.

name: "Tukakahumai," Family bach in Tolaga Bay
description:
With uninterrupted views across the river to the beach cliffs, our freshly presented Kiwi bach is perfect for families wanting some rest and relaxation.

At the end of a no-through road, this family home offers low-key accommodation for small or large groups. Easy stroll to the river, shops & cafes. Five-minute drive to the Wharf or Blue Waters beaches.

Please note that it's not possible to walk to the beach you see from the front deck - there's a lot of scrub and a tidal river in the way!
neighborhood_overview:
Outdoor adventures await! Hike to Cook's Cove, stroll along the historic wharf, climb the cliffs above Blue Waters surf beach. Great body-boarding, surfing and swimming beaches, patrolled through summer. Fishing charters. Golf and lawn bowls club. 40-minute drive to the world-famous Rere Rockfalls.

Have a meal at the Tolaga Bay pub and cafe. Awesome fish and chips from the riverside takeaway.

description:

neighborhood_overview:
Te Awanga started life as a beach house settlement for people from Napier and Hastings in the 1950s. During the last 40 years it has become a thriving community of people who permanently live here. The community as such has been retained by having one road in and one road out. The road through Te Awanga ends at Clifton, the main departure point for the trip to the Gannet Colony. If you are walking to the Cape, be sure and check the tides.

The Village is generally crime free but please lock doors and cars as an extra precaution. Warm summer nights often see locals enjoying an after dark walk. Dont worry they don't bight!
